[suggestions]
  LENS     unicode-skeptic
           The worldview assumes ASCII-like text. A Unicode lens would challenge every definition (word, character, line) and surface internationalization gaps.
  LENS     unix-purist
           Would evaluate every design decision against strict Unix philosophy — stdin, exit codes, signal handling, composability with other tools.
  QUESTION Should this tool try to match GNU wc output exactly, or intentionally diverge?
           This single decision cascades into output format, flag naming, edge case behavior, and whether existing scripts can use it as a drop-in replacement.
  QUESTION What is the intended audience — developers scripting in pipelines, or casual users checking document length?
           The audience determines whether machine-readable output, pretty formatting, or both matter. It also shapes error messaging tone.
  SOURCE   https://unicode.org/reports/tr29/
           UAX #29 defines Unicode word boundaries — the authoritative spec for 'what is a word' across all languages.
  QUESTION Should the tool support counting custom units (sentences, paragraphs, tokens)?
           In the age of LLMs, token counting is arguably more useful than word counting. This could be the differentiator from wc.

